    <header>
        <h1>Velocity is a Commodity.<br>Judgment is the Differentiator.</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">How artificial intelligence is quietly shifting the bar for what exceptional engineering leadership looks like.</p>
    </header>

    <main>
        <p class="lead-text">A year ago, I thought AI would mostly make teams faster. Better productivity, less grunt work, more output per engineer. Useful, but incremental.</p>

        <div class="highlight-quote">
            What I underestimated was this: AI doesn't just change how fast you decide. It changes what decisions you're even capable of making.
        </div>

        <p>In system design, you've always been constrained by what you could reasonably model in your head—or in a room. Complexity beyond a certain threshold gets simplified, deferred, or ignored. Not because technology leaders are lazy, but because human cognitive bandwidth is finite.</p>

        <div class="ceiling-box">
            AI breaks that ceiling.
        </div>

        <div class="capability-list">
            <h3>The New Paradigm of System Architecture</h3>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 20px;">Expanding execution constraints opens up a entirely new tier of system capabilities. Suddenly, you can:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Pressure-test a complex architecture against 10 distinct edge cases simultaneously instead of 3.</li>
                <li>Model the deep downstream impacts of a product decision across your legacy ERP/SAP integrations, data layers, and the customer journey at the same time.</li>
                <li>Ask much harder architecture questions significantly earlier, when errors are still cheap to fix.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <p>That is fundamentally not a productivity gain. That is a permanent **decision quality shift**.</p>

        <p>And it means the bar for what "good engineering leadership" looks like is quietly moving. Leaders who use artificial intelligence to think deeper will consistently outcompete those who use it to simply move faster.</p>

        <div class="contrast-container">
            <div class="contrast-card">
                <div class="card-label label-commodity">The Old Paradigm</div>
                <div class="card-title">Speed</div>
                <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; margin-bottom: 0;">Moving fast, shipping volume, and optimizing individual lines of code per minute. A metric that has officially become a commodity.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="contrast-card highlighted">
                <div class="card-label label-differentiator">The New Frontier</div>
                <div class="card-title">Judgment</div>
                <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; margin-bottom: 0; color: #115e59;">Orchestrating high-order systems, understanding side effects, and evaluating deep system architectures accurately.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <p>The core question facing modern organizations isn't whether you're using AI in your workflows. It's whether you're using it to make <strong>better decisions</strong> or just more of the same ones.</p>

        <div class="takeaway-quote">
            Speed was always a commodity. Judgment was always the differentiator. AI is now widening that gap—fast.
        </div>
    </main>

